Subject: fmha bwd: make persistent deterministic nsplits num_cus-independent

The deterministic non-group (persistent) backward derived its dq_acc split
count from get_num_cus(): nsplits was a compressed function of the CU count in
PrepareWorkspaceHost, PrepareWorkspaceDevice, and GetWorkspaceDeviceSizeUpperBound,
while the persistent kernel writes split index
  i_split = ceil((job % jobs_per_head) / jobs_per_worker)
with jobs_per_worker = ceil(total_jobs / gridDim.x).

This is only self-consistent when the num_cus used to compute nsplits exactly
matches gridDim.x at launch. get_num_cus() queries the current device's
multiProcessorCount, which differs across gfx archs (e.g. gfx942 vs gfx950) and
can be sampled at a different time/device than the launch grid; when it does not
match, i_split reaches or exceeds nsplits and the kernel writes/reduces past the
dq_acc split region -> silent corruption (observed as zeroed results on gfx942
deterministic backward, batch/BSHD mode).

Use the num_cus-independent upper bound jobs_per_head = ceil(seqlen_k / kN0) for
nsplits at all three sites. It always bounds the kernel's max i_split
(< jobs_per_head for any worker count), unused splits stay zero (NeedsZeroDqAcc()
is true for the persistent kernel, so the reduction is unaffected), and it matches
the seqlen-based dq_acc floor TE already reserves -- so no extra workspace.

